<subSubSection pageId="45" pageNumber="46" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1436,151,378]" box="[198,905,191,218]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,331,191,217]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Etymology</emphasis>
. This species is named after Dr. Tatsuya Niisato.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1436,151,378]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,275,231,257]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Notes.</emphasis>
Male is externally indistinguishable from 
<taxonomicName authority="Yoshitomi &amp; Ruta, 2010" authorityName="Yoshitomi &amp; Ruta" authorityYear="2010" box="[779,1048,232,257]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chiangmaiensis" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[779,1048,232,257]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Scirtes chiangmaiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1057,1121,232,258]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
It can be easily identified, however, on the basis of morphology of male genitalia: penis is much longer than parameres. Female very similar to the one of 
<taxonomicName authority="Yoshitomi &amp; Ruta, 2010" authorityName="Yoshitomi &amp; Ruta" authorityYear="2010" box="[399,594,312,337]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laosensis" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[399,594,312,337]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Scirtes laosensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[603,669,312,338]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, but differs in having pronotal margins lightened, yellowish, and yellow scutellum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
